# Workflow Logging Rule

## Purpose

Enforce complete workflow observability by logging every skill invocation and command execution to `logs/workflow.md`.

## Activation

This rule is **always-on**. It activates automatically on every agent action — you do not invoke it.

## Behavior

When any agent action occurs, this rule intercepts and logs. Use the **exact** formats below so logs match the README spec and remain parseable.

### 1. Command Start/End

When a workflow command (`/plan`, `/execute`, `/review`) is invoked:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] COMMAND:<command> - START
> Input: "<user request>"
```

When complete:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] COMMAND:<command> - COMPLETE
> <summary or plan ID if applicable>
```

### 2. Skill Invocation

When an agent invokes a skill:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] SKILL:<skill-name> - INVOKED
> <skill action description>
```

When skill completes:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] SKILL:<skill-name> - Complete
> <result summary>
```

Use skill names from README: `solution-design`, `database-design`, `security-review`, `devops-pipeline`.

### 3. Decision Logged

When an agent makes a significant decision:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] DECISION: <decision description>
```

Example: `[DECISION] Tech stack: Express + TypeScript + PostgreSQL`

### 4. Rule Applied

When a rule is applied (e.g. coding standards check):

```
### [HH:MM:SS] RULE:<rule-name>: <outcome>
```

Example: `[RULE:coding-standards] Validated: ESLint config present`

### 5. Warning/Issue

When a warning or issue is identified:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] WARN: <description>
```

Example: `[WARN] No rate limiting detected in API design`

### 6. Error Logged

When an error occurs:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] ERROR: <error description>
```

## Log Location

All entries are appended to: `logs/workflow.md`

The log file is an **append-only** record. Entries are never modified or deleted.

## Log Format (match README)

Each workflow run MUST start with:

```markdown
---
## Workflow Run: YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ
**Task**: <short task description>
**Command**: /<plan|execute|review>
```

Then use `### [HH:MM:SS] EVENT - STATE` for each line. This matches the README "What Gets Logged" and "Example Log Entry" sections.

## Example

```markdown
---
## Workflow Run: 2026-03-19T10:30:00Z
**Task**: Add authentication to user API
**Command**: /plan

### [10:30:01] COMMAND:plan - START
> Input: "Add authentication to user API"

### [10:30:02] SKILL:solution-design - INVOKED
> Analyzing requirements...
> - Identified 3 functional requirements (login, logout, token refresh)

### [10:30:10] SKILL:solution-design - Complete
> Output: 3 components identified

### [10:30:15] COMMAND:plan - COMPLETE
> Plan saved to plans/plan-20260319-103000.md
```
